This was our first Burn. Extreme heat and dust storms are the norm in Black Rock Desert, but once in a blue moon it sprinkles rain. This time, the playa received two to three months worth of rain in 24 hours. As the storm rolled in, our camp assembled a team meeting to discuss management of our impending catastrophic doom. Topics of discussion were safety, shelter, electricity, and the inevitable rising waste levels of the porta potties. When our camp lead mentioned Woodstock 99' it was the first time we considered just how bad things could get.

Minutes into the meeting, the clouds broke behind us revealing the most perfect double rainbow one could ever imagine. The playa erupted. Burners emerged from their tents barefooted, cheering and howling at the sky. The air was electric. For a moment, we could collectively pause and appreciate a silver lining amongst an absolute shit storm. The desert ground which had become a disgusting muddy ice rink, transformed into a spectacular once-in-a lifetime photo op. As the sky turned pink and the rainbow began to fade, our camp mates retreated for cover. The moment was ours. We exchanged a few words, we both cried, and she said yes. With toes caked in mud, and a shiny new ring on one finger, we walked back to camp beaming. The meeting resumed: "Alright everyone, with a show of hands, who's willing to shit in a bucket?"

I’m just another kooky tourist enjoying the majestic view of the landscape from ‘Forrest Gump’ on the road to Monument Valley. This place is constantly littered with delirious pedestrians, swarming to the middle of the road for “their” special shot. I suspect at least a thousand photos are taken here each day, perhaps every couple hours. But I wonder… does anyone have THIS shot? Wait, don’t tell me. I don’t want to know. #imspecial 

📸: @itsjasonlucas

A moment of gratitude. Flashback to 2010, the year I last dared to whip up a demo reel for my film school dreams. Spoiler: My submission, packed with bike stunts, scooter clips, and cringe comedy sketches, hit SO hard that Langara College had no choice but to roll out the red carpet and usher me into their four-month dramatic film course. Looking back, it’s now clear the administration was likely budgeting with a coin jar and needed my pennies.

Now, as I watch this mishmash of clips, the cringe is fading, and I’m getting misty-eyed, recognizing the significant leap in my film journey. I am grateful!

Reflecting on a decade of creative mischief, I send big thanks to the extraordinary humans who rallied behind these projects. To the millions who tuned in—probably seeking sweet cat videos but found us instead—bless your curious clicks.

It’s been a blast. At the core of it all, a tight-knit crew has been my unwavering support, essentially becoming my second family. To my slightly more biological family, endless love – you’re the real MVPs! While crafting visually stunning content is crucial, laughter rules in the @ifhtfilms world. But hold onto your chuckles, my friends! The adventure isn’t ending here, and who knows, in the next decade, Langara might erect a statue in my honour. Stay tuned for the grand unveiling! 🎉

Thank you!
